{
  "answer": "**Āṅgirasa Smṛti** classifies sins hierarchically into **great sins** (requiring an assembly of 100 or 1,000 Brahmins), **greatest sins** (1,000), **secondary sins** (assembly of 50), and **minor sins** (small assembly). The five great sinners are a Brahmin-killer, a gold-thief, a liquor-drinker, a defiler of the Guru's bed, and one who associates with these. The fallen (*patitāḥ*) include killers of women or men, defilers of maidens, and cow-killers; secondary sins are \"innumerable\" like cow-killing.[^1][^2][^3]\n\n**Kātyāyana Smṛti** refers to **major sins** repeatedly (e.g., homicide, theft, drinking liquor, intercourse with a preceptor's wife), for which representatives are forbidden and ordeals or banishment apply, distinguishing them from lesser offenses.[^4]\n\n**Bṛhaspati Smṛti** mentions **great sins** in procedural contexts (e.g., accusations requiring ordeals), but without enumeration.[^5]\n\n**Kūñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana** classifies sins by source into **three kinds** from body (killing, treachery, stealing property/wives), speech, and mind (faithless, delighting in faults), leading to suffering in Yama's realm.[^6]\n\n**No other works** in the corpus provide systematic classifications (e.g., Cynewulf poems and poetry mention sins generically; no \"seven deadly sins\" or equivalents). \n\n[^1]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [Chapter 1/translation/#p-5068cf](#p-5068cf).\n[^2]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [Chapter 1/translation/#p-cafcb4](#p-cafcb4).\n[^3]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [Chapter 1/translation/#p-39c7b4](#p-39c7b4).\n[^4]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, [Chapter 11/translation/#p-a0b028](#p-a0b028).\n[^5]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, [Chapter 1/translation/#p-182b0c](#p-182b0c).\n[^6]: Kūñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana, [Chapter 1/translation/#p-650c77](#p-650c77).",
